The "Additional files"\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\qj

\fs22 \cf0 \ulnone \
Since version 1.16.0, LaTeXiT provides the palette entitled "Additional files".\
You are certainly aware that during a classical, command-line, LaTeX compilation, the engine can use files in the current directory : this can be useful to reference images, non-standard packages (sty) or other resources in your document. Formerly, LaTeXiT did not allow that, since as a user of this graphical interface, you had no access to this "working directory" of the underlying LaTeX engine. It is a temporary folder, the path being subject to changes.\
The palette "Additional files" fixes that. Drop in it files or folders, and LaTeXiT will behave as if they were in its working directory. Technically, this is just a bunch of symbolic links : your files are neither moved, nor copied.\
