\fs22 \cf0 \ulnone \
LaTeXiT relies on a functional LaTeX installation. But if you do not know what LaTeX is, you may find it difficult to find and install it. So, here are some very basis explanations, as guidance if you need it.\
\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\qj\pardirnatural
\cf0 LaTeX is not really a single program. It is a bunch of executable files and data files that work together. So, like with Linux, you will find LaTeX *distributions*. A distribution of LaTeX is a set of files that somebody gathered and organized so that once installed, it would work.\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\qj
\cf0 On MacOS X, there are two well-known distributions : TexLive and MacTeX, the second one embedding the first one.\
- TexLive\
TexLive ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.tug.org/texlive"}}{\fldrslt http://www.tug.org/texlive}}) is a  multi-platform LaTeX distribution.\
- MacTeX\
MacTeX ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.tug.org/mactex"}}{\fldrslt http://www.tug.org/mactex}}) is a TeXLive distribution embedding some more apps specific to MacOS X. It is provided through a simple dmg file downloaded on the website (a few hundreds of megabytes, though)\
\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\qj\pardirnatural
\cf0 Once such a distribution expanded, LaTeX is installed on your computer. But if you were not warned, you would not even notice that ! In fact, LaTeX has no graphical front-end, the programs are Unix-oriented and can only be called on the command line (using the /Application/Utilities/Terminal)\
However, do not worry : there exists graphical interfaces to use LaTeX in a more user friendly manner. These are third-party software, most of the time free. LaTeXiT is one of them : it allows to typeset  small equations. To write big documents, you would rather use TexShop or iTexMac (for instance), which are designed for that.\
